Workshop 2

In workshop 1 we started our adventures in R by exploring our working environment and the various data types at our disposal. Today, well pick up where we left off by learning how to keep our environment and data clean and tidy. Now that youve had a chance to set up your R environment and learn the basics, well also transition to a lot more group working and a lot less of me talking at you.

1 Introduction

1.1 Learning Objectives

  1. Learn how to install and load packages
  2. Become fluent loading data from external sources
  3. Develop good practices for keeping your environment organized
  4. Learn some key functions needed to start pre-processing your data

2 Today: Data Wrangling in R

2.1 Outline

  • Although we wont talk about it live, one of my goals is to demonstrate some helpful but non-obvious R features, so Ill sprinkle them in as they come up

  • Well then learn how to read .xlsx, .csv and .tsv, both local and remote using the {vroom} and {readxl} packages

2.2 Bonus: Negative indexing

In array-type objects, you can index using a negative address to exclude the given element from the return. You can see this in the following:

vector_of_10 <- 1:10
vector_of_10[-9] # Exclude the 9th element
## [1]  1  2  3  4  5  6  7  8 10
vector_of_10[-c(1, 10)] # Exclude the first and 10th elements
## [1] 2 3 4 5 6 7 8 9

You can similarly use this in lists and data frames, as such

my_df <- data.frame(A = 1:4, B = LETTERS[1:4], C = letters[1:4], D = rnorm(4))
my_df[, -1] # Exclude the first column
##   B C          D
## 1 A a -0.8976092
## 2 B b -1.0383335
## 3 C c -0.2408803
## 4 D d -0.2964772
my_df[-1, ] # Exclude the first row
##   A B C          D
## 2 2 B b -1.0383335
## 3 3 C c -0.2408803
## 4 4 D d -0.2964772
my_list <- list(A = 1:4, B = LETTERS[1:4], C = letters[1:4], D = rnorm(4))
my_list[-1] # Exclude the first list element
## $B
## [1] "A" "B" "C" "D"
## 
## $C
## [1] "a" "b" "c" "d"
## 
## $D
## [1]  0.4621573  0.3481591 -0.1744435 -1.3074827

2.3 Beyond base R

One of the strong sides of R is the abundance of high quality libraries that you can leverage to make your analysis faster and easier. Today, well start our session by installing two libraries that well lean on heavily.

To install external packages from CRAN, its as simple as running install.packages and waiting! Lets get started by installing {dplyr}, {vroom}, and {readxl}.

install.packages("dplyr")
install.packages("vroom")
install.packages("readxl")

You can install CRAN packages by running install.packages and passing the name of the package. If youre running R from the command line, you may be prompted to select a mirror to use. You only have to install packages once.

Of course, there are also a great many packages on GitHub that havent been added to CRAN that you still may want to use in your analyses. One library that makes it very easy to install these is called {devtools} (installed simply as install.packages('devtools')), which allows you to install from GitHub, Bioconductor or Bitbucket using the appropriate devtools::install_* function. One such package is {Rphenograph}, which must be installed through GitHub. We probably wont use it in our workshops, but to give you a sense of how {devtools} works, you can install {Rphenograph} by running devtools::install_github('JinmiaoChenLab/Rphenograph').

Once these are finished installing, the packages will be available for use on your local machine. You can check this out by navigating to the Packages panel in your RStudio instance.

Just because these are installed doesnt mean theyre loaded. You need to load the packages to use them using the library function, as follows:

library(dplyr)
library(vroom)
library(readxl)

You should typically load these libraries at the very top of your R scripts to stay organized and make sure theyre accessible whenever you run the code.

Load any required libraries at the top of your scripts using the library function.

2.4 Reading data

A common task in data analysis is loading your data into R in the first place. This functionality exists in base R (see the auto-complete options for read.), but implementations in {readr} and {vroom} are much faster.

Its unfortunate that not all of these exist in one single package, but to summarize:

Task Library
Reading delimited (.csv, .tsv, etc) files {vroom}
Reading Excel files {readxl}

2.4.1 Reading delimited data from local files

Well demonstrate this with data from FiveThirtyEight.

covid_data <- vroom::vroom('data/covid-19-polls-master/covid_approval_polls_adjusted.csv')
## Rows: 1,933
## Columns: 19
## Delimiter: ","
## chr [11]: subject, modeldate, party, startdate, enddate, pollster, grade, population, mult...
## dbl [ 7]: samplesize, weight, influence, approve, disapprove, approve_adjusted, disapprove...
## lgl [ 1]: tracking
## 
## Use `spec()` to retrieve the guessed column specification
## Pass a specification to the `col_types` argument to quiet this message

It is sometimes convenient to explicitly specify the column types when loading the data, which can be accomplished simply by specifying the col_types argument. This way, we can ensure we get the data type we want instead of letting {vroom} guess for us.

covid_data <- vroom::vroom('data/covid-19-polls-master/covid_approval_polls_adjusted.csv', col_types = 'f?f??ffdfddfldddd?c')

Its good practice to check the head (the first few rows) of your loaded data to ensure it matches what you expect it to look like. You can also glimpse at it (some people prefer this view) or simply peek at the colnames.

head(covid_data)

2.4.2 Reading delimited data from remote sources

It is mostly unimportant whether your data is stored in your local filesystem or remotely; you can read the data using the same method calls. Well see this using a .tsv file from the Rivas Lab (prepared from 17th IHIW NGS HLA data). Note that this file is a tab-delimited file rather than a comma-delimited one, but {vroom} autodetects this for us and reads it appropriately. You can also specify this explicitly using the delim argument.

Furthermore, since the column names in the underlying data are not standard (like #Locus and Ethnicity/Country, we can assign more convenient names in one go).

ihiw_data <- vroom::vroom('https://github.com/rivas-lab/covid19/raw/158f8c42387a6368dcb236d0f0d5c87561193966/HLA/17ihiw-Family-FQ.tsv',
                          col_names = c('locus', 'allele', 'ethnicity', 'frequency', 'allele_count', 'family_count', 'sample_count'),
                          col_types = 'fcfdddd')

2.4.3 Reading Excel files

Excel files can be read into R using the {readxl} package. As the name suggests, it is only capable of reading Excel files (not writing them, although there are other packages for this).

Well demonstrate this using some data that was collected for this GitHub project on profiling internet usage of different users. Note that since Excel files can have multiple sheets, we need to make sure we read the correct one (which can be accomplished by either browsing it in Excel, or using the excel_sheets function to output which sheets are present).

readxl::excel_sheets('data/internet-users.xlsx')
## [1] "Sheet1"
internet_data <- readxl::read_excel('data/internet-users.xlsx')

2.4.4 Reading R Data files

Its often convenient to save R objects to disk with all their proper structure so that you can read them in for later analysis. This is easily done using saveRDS and readRDS. Because this is very similar to the above, we wont demonstrate this with real data. Theres only one thing to keep in mind: when the object your saving has a class defined by a non-base package (such as a {Seurat} object, which well learn about later), you need to remember to load that package to interact properly with your object.

2.5 Data wrangling in R

Its often the case that the data that we load is not in the most convenient form to address our questions and so, we must get familiar with the main tools to work with our data. A lot of our basic data wrangling can be done using {dplyr} and typically involves a few key functions:

Function name Purpose
mutate Adds or modifies column(s) to an existing data frame
summarize Creates a new data frame by summarizing all observations as specified
group_by Group a data frame by certain column(s)
filter Filter a data frame, only keeping rows where some expression evaluates to TRUE
arrange Sort the rows of a data frame according to some column

Well get a sense for how these work by doing some toy analysis on the data we loaded above.

2.5.1 Mutations

Your task: The data has columns for approve and disapprove: the percentage of respondents that either approve or disapprove of the subject. These do not necessarily sum to 100% as respondents may have failed to respond or responded with something else. Create a column, other that contains the percentage of respondents who responded they neither approve or disapprove.

# YOUR CODE HERE
covid_data <- mutate(covid_data,
                     other = 100 - (approve + disapprove))

Like we mentioned before, mutate can also modify an existing column.

Your task: We can see above that some data-looking columns arent read as dates, but rather as characters, because their format isnt automatically detected. There exists a built-in R function called as.Date which can convert characters into date objects, given a proper format (the relevant formatting is as follows: %d represents the date, %m the month and %Y the year). For example, as.Date('13/01/2020', format = '%d/%m/%Y') will be interpreted as January 13, 2020. Convert the four date columns that are stored as characters into their proper date representation.

# YOUR CODE HERE
covid_data <- mutate(covid_data,
                     modeldate = as.Date(modeldate, format = '%m/%d/%Y'),
                     startdate = as.Date(startdate, format = '%m/%d/%Y'),
                     enddate = as.Date(enddate, format = '%m/%d/%Y'),
                     timestamp = as.Date(timestamp, format = '%m/%d/%Y'))

2.5.2 Groups and Summaries

Groups behave somewhat unexpectedly in {dplyr}: instead of changing the structure of the data itself, grouping information is stored in an attribute and the data itself looks exactly the same (you can see this using the attr function, the groups function or by printing the grouped data frame and examining the output). Mutations, summaries, and other {dplyr} functions typically respect these grouping variables, allowing you to do some powerful aggregations.

Your task: Create a data frame, pollster_statistics which contains three columns: pollster, mean_approve_adjusted and mean_disapprove_adjusted, such that each pollster is paired with the mean adjusted approval and disapproval rate across all polls.

# YOUR CODE HERE
pollster_statistics <- summarize(group_by(covid_data, pollster),
                                 mean_approval_adjusted = mean(approve_adjusted, na.rm = T),
                                 mean_disapprove_adjusted = mean(disapprove_adjusted, na.rm = T))

2.5.4 Piping

Now is a good time to learn about a very useful language feature that {dplyr} introduces: the pipe. By clever design, all {dplyr} functions require the data as their first argument (remember how we called mutate, summarize, filter and group_by?). In this way, instead of saving intermediate representations, we can simply pipe our data into the next processing step. This has two major advantages:

  1. We dont need to save objects that are in-transit between more useful representations
  2. It makes our code easier to read (left-to-right, top-to-bottom)

The pipe (%>%) takes whatever is on the left-hand-side and inserts it as the first argument to the expression in the right-hand-side.

One example of this simplification can be seen below:

toy_data <- data.frame(UUID = LETTERS[1:20],
                       grade = runif(20, max = 100))

# Without a pipe...
toy_data_not_failed <- filter(mutate(toy_data,
                                lettergrade = case_when(
                                  grade >= 90 ~ 'A',
                                  grade >= 80 ~ 'B',
                                  grade >= 70 ~ 'C',
                                  grade >= 60 ~ 'D',
                                  TRUE ~ 'F'
                                )), lettergrade != 'F')

# With a pipe...
toy_data_not_failed <- toy_data %>%
  mutate(lettergrade = case_when(
    grade >= 90 ~ 'A',
    grade >= 80 ~ 'B',
    grade >= 70 ~ 'C',
    grade >= 60 ~ 'D',
    TRUE ~ 'F'
    )) %>%
  filter(lettergrade != 'F')

As you can see, the code reads much more logically when organized effectively with pipes.

Your task: Rewrite the following code in one single pipeline.

covid_data_feb <- filter(covid_data, months(startdate) == 'February')
covid_data_feb_clean <- mutate(covid_data_feb,
                               largesamplesize = samplesize > 500,
                               party = recode(party,
                                              D = 'Democrats',
                                              I = 'Independents',
                                              R = 'Republicans'))
covid_data_feb_clean_final <- summarise(group_by(covid_data_feb_clean, pollster, party),
                                        sufficiently_large = sum(largesamplesize) > n() / 3)
covid_data_feb_piped <- covid_data %>%
  filter(months(startdate) == 'February') %>%
  mutate(largesamplesize = samplesize > 500,
         party = recode(party,
                        D = 'Democrats',
                        I = 'Independents',
                        R = 'Republicans')) %>%
  group_by(pollster, party) %>%
  summarise(sufficiently_large = sum(largesamplesize) > n() / 3)

2.5.4.1 Bonus: Advanced pipes

As you know, pipes feed the left-hand argument to the first argument in the right-hand expression. What you may not know is that this piped object can be passed around at will since it gets assigned to the name . (the period). This effectively lets you pass the piped object to multiple different places in a function, as the following example demonstrates:

scores <- rnorm(30)

scores %>% abs %>% log(base = sum(.)) # Use the sum of |scores| as the logarithm base.
##  [1]  0.011129248 -0.397062654  0.162268911 -0.845834484 -0.126557758
##  [6] -0.144381963  0.243450495 -0.049300166 -0.247019999 -0.004180707
## [11] -0.528366392 -0.259204913 -0.342656159 -0.055447229 -0.930129805
## [16] -1.303143425 -0.421603503 -0.217867545 -0.072301123 -0.094538490
## [21] -0.313396087 -1.314159994 -0.239969552 -0.370418347 -0.428931432
## [26] -0.407008519 -0.749901965 -1.121455623 -0.828482159  0.239044078

Theres also a few special looking assignment functions that allow you to perform assignments in a pipe, which allows you to modify row names, column names etc. without having to separate them from your pipeline. These include rownames<-, colnames<- and more. Since these arent valid R names (ie. they include <-, which are reserved characters), you must surround these names with backticks (`) to allow R to interpret them properly.

my_colnames <- c('UUID', 'score')
my_data <- data.frame(1:10, rnorm(10)) %>% `colnames<-`(my_colnames) %>% `rownames<-`(LETTERS[1:10])

head(my_data)
##   UUID       score
## A    1  1.08084178
## B    2 -0.03362777
## C    3  0.49376756
## D    4 -0.07923031
## E    5 -0.91558770
## F    6  0.78838318

Finally, although it is only really useful in a select few instances (and even then, it gets messy quickly so you may prefer to avoid it), since the right-hand-side of pipes accept any general expression, you can do even more interesting things by passing a code block where you can perform interim calculations, print things, and etc. before returning your result. As usual, the . is used to refer to the piped object.

my_data %>% {
  print('You can print from here...')

  # You can assign variables here for temporary storage
  some_temp_value <- .$UUID * .$score
  mutate(., new_value = some_temp_value)
}

## 6     6  0.78838318  4.73029908
